<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission by the RAC Foundation for Motoring to the Transport Select Committee’s Inquiry into Road Safety</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">RAC Foundation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> (SRN 010)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The RAC Foundation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">is a charity which explores the economic, mobility, safety and environmental issues relating to roads and responsible road users. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Independent and authoritative research, carried out for the public benefit, is central to the Foundation’s activities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The RAC Foundation welcomes the July 2013 changes in policy towards strategic roads. In his Foreword</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">White Paper</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> the Secretary of State claims</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> “the most radical change to the management of our highways in nearly half a century, and the biggest investment in improvements since the seventies.”  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">There is also to be more funding for national and loca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">l roads maintenance and for improvements to some local road schemes.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The programme of Manag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ed Motorways is to be extended and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> new concept of E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">xpressways has been introduced, for major dual carriageways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Most importantly, there is to be a roads strategy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">and a five-year planning cycle with committed funding and delivery</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> given the force of the law. The Highways Agency is to be reformed as a separate, government-owned company.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">There is a discussion currently on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the nature of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> “watchdog” to ensure delivery and protect the interests of road users as consumers—something that is uniquely absent amongst the public utilities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The Government has committed to publishing a National Policy Statement on roads and railways for public cons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ultation before the end of 2013. This is a vital background </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">that has been absent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">for discussion of coherent strategic policies, including decisions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">that have already been made </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">to proceed with major new road</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">nd </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">HS2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">All this constitutes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">an attractive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">package of reforms. The next step is to secure delivery</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span></li></ol><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">A stop-start</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">history for roads</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">In 1989 the Conservative Government pu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">blished “Roads for Prosperity”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">This promised “the largest road building programme since the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> Romans”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">In the event </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">little of what </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">had been promised was delivered because of funding difficulties.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The Labour administration’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> 1998 White Paper, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">A New Deal for Transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">further cut the roads programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. But t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">he aspiration to solve the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">transport capacity problem by improved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> public transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">unrealistic and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Ten Year Plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> of 2000 did show a substantial incr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ease in strategic roads funding. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Again, this plan was not delivered, partly because the railway accident at Hatfield forced an unanticipated increase in  funding in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">railways at the expense of other modes.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Over the later years of the Blair administration road building plans were substantially expan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ded, without fanfare.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> But, once again, the Coalition Government of 2010 severely cut both capital and revenue spending in n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ational and local roads in the Spending Review of 2010. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The plans for railways survived more or less unscathed, not least because of the protection offered by the statutory system of the five-year High Level Output </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Specification and Statement of Funds </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">This is an important lesson for the present roads reform.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">At one time similar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> “stop-start</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">” patterns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> occurred with London Underground and National Rail funding. But administrative reforms have succeeded in stabilising funding. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">he strategic roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> have become “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">exposed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">” as the only major budget item over which transport ministers have short-term control.</span></li></ol><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">How will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">so improving the environment?</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Taking the recently revised national traffic forecasts at face value </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> illustrates some of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">undesirable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">consequenc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">es of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">continued </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">inaction (Paragraph 1.25). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The maps on pages 20 and 21 show the geographical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">locations of the deteriorations.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> as a whole did relatively well in the 2013 Spending Review, especially on the capital side (see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Investing in Britain’s Future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, HM Treasury, Cm 8669, June 2013, Table 1.A). Between 2015-16 and 2020-21 the capital inv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">estment budget for the HA increases by a factor of 2.5 and by the end of this period it nearly reaches the level of spend for Network Rail (though  both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">topped by HS2).  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">This growth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">for roads </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">appears to be on a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">reduced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> base: the £1.5 bn for 2015-16 r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">epresents a cut from the capital spend of £1.9 bn for 2014-15 which appears in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> HA’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> current business plan. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">he government has inserted significant extra “pinchpoint” and other funds into the 2013-14 and 2014-15 programmes (£514m and £827m respectively)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and these transient injections are the reason for the apparent reduction in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the 2015</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">-16 plans.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">It is for the government to expound the detail of how this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">markedly increased</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> level of spend on roads will mitigate the problems it has, correctly, identified. But it is fair to say that it will certainly be a substantial help.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">As the Prime Minister has correctly observed (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">speech, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">19 March 2012) “There’s nothi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ng green about a traf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">fic jam—a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">nd gridlock holds the economy back”.  The increased traffic can (and must) be accommodated within the Committee on Climate Change’s overall carbon emission targets, providing that the efficiency targets and regulations for new vehicles are realise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">d. This is also true of most detriments to air quality.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Improving the road network will allow more traffic to flow—that is the point of the improvement. This “generated” traffic is not necessarily a bad thing and from an environmental point of vie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">w it may</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> represent a net gain: t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">he problem being addressed is that traffic will grow in any case</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> because of population growth and economic recovery</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and it is less damaging to provide for the extra traffic than to allow all traffic to suffer increased congestion. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">roviding more capacity will allow traffic to move more efficiently and thus with fewer emissions than would be the case otherwise.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">As the White Paper notes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> increased roads expenditure creates opportunities to make en</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">vironmental improvements. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">t is possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> to create: opportunities to bypass villages and protected sites; opportunities to invest in safety improvements, quieter road surfaces and environmental safeguards.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">It is very welcome that the July 2013 White Paper contains a commitment to publish for consultation a National </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Policy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Statement for surface networks (roads and railways) by the end of 2013. The government and its predecessor committed to producing a series</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">f National Policy Statements: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">we have been promised the one on roads and railways for years.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> Important decisions on roads, rail and high speed rail have been made in the absence of an explicit, coherent policy context.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The government is—rightly—keen on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">attracting private funds to invest in transport infrastructure: for instance in major rail freight terminals and the A14 road improvement scheme. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">With the assurance on timely decisions that the NPS system is designed to provide p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">rivate enterprise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">is more l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ikely to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">risk time and money on promoting a scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The Secretary of State says in the White Paper</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">(para. 4.19)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> “we are particularly keen for investment decisions on road and rail to happen in concert.” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">t is welcome that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> has started a series of route-based strategies (White Paper, p54), but these will not carry credibility if they give inadequate attention to the non-road modes, even if those other modes, in practice, can only realistically achieve a small share of the ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">rket.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">How reliable is the Government’s forecast for growth in demand for the strategic road network? How should the Government deal with uncertainty in its forecast? </span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Whilst there is always room for improvement we think</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the revised, July 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">National Traf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">fic Forecasts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> are soundly based and plausible, as are the ranges under different assumptions. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">forecasts and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ranges are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> largely driven by demographic change, population growth and economic growth.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> take account of the limited opportunities for o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ther modes to cater for the growth (nationally, although rail travel has been growing, it still only accounts for 9% of mechanised passenger miles and a similar proportion of freight). There is a debate to be had about the extent to which it is realistic t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">o expect major changes in the locations of homes and jobs to reduce the need to travel.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">These forecasts (and the local disaggregation that lies behind them) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">are a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> good basis for discussion of what is likely to happen if there were no increase in strategic road capacity, and what the benefits might be of investment in capacity.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">forecasts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">it clear that under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> any reasonable set of assumptions substantial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">oad </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">traffic growth must be expected by 2040.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The magnitude of this growth is uncertain. So far as we are aware, the government has not said anything about how it intends</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> to deal with the uncertainties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. The tradition has always been to work with the cent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ral value. This approach has long been criticised, going back at least as far as the 1975 first report of the independent Committee on Trunk Road Assessment (the Leitch Committee). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">A more considered approach would consider the implications of “getting it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> wrong”. If we provide for more traffic than actually occurs we will regret a waste of public resources.  If more traffic appears than has been provided for we will regret the congestion and the missed opportunities to deal with it at a lower cost and disr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">uption than is now necessary.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We advocate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> move to pay-as-you go charging in place of some or all of conventional road taxation. Direct user charging, as well as providing a revenue stream, creates a better environment for private sector participation in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> roads development and operation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> It also provides efficient demand management, still needed in any realistic roads improvement programme and a hedge </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">against getting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> our demand forecasts wrong (as we will).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> There will inevitably be some congestion at pea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">k times but the intensity and duration of this can be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> managed by varying price,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> thus widening the range o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">f reasonably efficient outcomes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">How can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network? What impact will new techno</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">logy have?</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The most effective way of improving the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network is simply to increase capacity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> in relation to the demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">But it will always be necessary to strive to manage the limited capacity available.  Not enough attention and resource has been devoted to this in the past—for example Traffic Officers have been beneficial on Motorways but their deployment on major all pur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">pose roads has been very limited.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The Managed Motorway programme has demonstrate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">d how significantly more can be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">safely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">squeezed out of our existing Motorway infrastructure. We welcome plans to extend this programme. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">However, on the hard pressed sections o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">f the motorway system, the projected increase in demand will be greater than these can accommodate. Also this programme does nothing for the capacity of the roads used to access Motorways or the junctions and that is often where the limiting  capacity cons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">traints occur.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The White Paper promises more attention will now be given to major, non-Motorway routes (paras. 2.16, 2.17): “Our major A roads play an important role in the economy, especially for freight. Roads like the A12 in the East of England, the A1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">9 in the North East and the A30 west into Cornwall are vital to their communities, and just as important as motorways are elsewhere in the country. … we want to give motorists a clear idea of what they can expect from these ‘expressways’. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> we will set c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">lear expectations for what expressways should be able to deliver…”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We strongly welcome this new initiative and hope it will be adequately funded.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We are aware that some commentators and commercial interests </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">claim m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">odern electronics and information </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">technologies will significantly increase capacity—for instance by enabling “road trains”, self-driving vehicles </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">and routing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> around congested locations. The RAC Foundation certainly recognises that these technologies are delivering and will continue to deli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ver important benefits </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">in terms of safety;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">economy; driver comfort and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">convenience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> navigation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> paying for motor insurance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">; and traffic management and planning.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">hey are important part of better management of the operation of roads. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Plainly, they can also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> make some contribution to reliability and efficiency of the strategic network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and they are likely to be most</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> effective on limited access roads.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ut</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> it remains to be demonstrated that they will offer more than a small </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">capacity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The exception t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">o this is that we now have a number of thoroughly proven technologies on off</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">r to enable pay-as-you-go charging. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Correctly applied that would dramatically improve reliability and efficiency.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">What mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK? </span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The reforms announced in July 2013 include a substantial increase i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">conventional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">capital funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> from the Exchequer.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">On 19th March 2012 the Prime Minister said: “We need to look at innovative approaches to the funding of our national roads – to increase investment to reduce congestion.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">e was hoping that institu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">tional infrastructure investors would provide the capital. The PM used the water industry as an analogy. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">In principle water is a good analogy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> (See</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Governing and Paying for England’s Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">S. Glaister, RAC Foundation, July 2010.) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">But</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, whilst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ater investment has been financed by the lenders it has been funded (that is, paid for) out of charges to end users. The same could be achieved for roads but only if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">there were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a defined cash flow, dedicated to servicing the interest and repayment of capit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">al. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">he P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> emphasised that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> “Road tolling is one option … but we are only considering this for new, not existing, capacity…” and since most schemes are incremental improvements to existing roads this stricture largely precludes the servicing of private cap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ital investment.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Against </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> background </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">of scarcity of public capital and prior commitments on increasing Network Rail’s debt and funding HS2, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">delivery of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">pu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">lic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">capital programme for roads will be hard work. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">A scheme to rebuild the A14</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, a road of int</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ernational significance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> an improved line of route was developed over the decade up to 2010, at a capital cost of £1.3bn. Broadly speaking there was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">local support for the solution. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">he scheme was withdrawn as “unaffordable” in the 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">10 Spending Review. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Since then the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> has been working to reinsta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">te a scheme. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">he government has now proposed a solution, essentially on the same line of route but with three-way funding. In addition to toll revenues there would be contributions from local interests, with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the residual coming from conventional Exchequer funding. The new scheme is more complex because additional subsidiary roads are proposed to enable local traffic to avoid the tolled sections and the cost has increased to £1.5bn.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Local governance is too frac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">tured over the geographical scale of this scheme and there are other, intense pressures on local funds. It seems the local contributions will not yield more than about £0.1bn.  The toll revenues are estimated to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">£30m pa, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">enough to fund only about £0.3bn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> of capital. There are significant problems of diversion onto untolled routes if a toll is imposed on only one road in a network. Further, tolls on this road do not sit well with the national lorry charging scheme which has been introduced on the grounds t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">hat foreign lorries do not pay tolls on UK roads whilst UK lorries do pay tolls to use major roads on the Continent.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The cancellation of the scheme in 2010 has caused years of delay and increased the costs to the extent that the costs to the Exchequer with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> tolls are not much reduced from what they would have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">with the 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, toll-free</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. The attempt to raise funding from tolling has added complexity, cost, local opposition and has little value as a 'pathfinder' project.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">There are some situations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">where tolling might be of value such as new discrete routes, Midland Expressway type situations or new estuarial crossings. Generally,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">geography dictates that it would be better to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">introduce pay-as-you-go charging</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> at a regional or national scale rat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">her than on isolated road</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The A14 is such vital scheme that work should start as soon as possible on the basis of conventional funding—like the other new strategic road capacity improvements announced in July 2013. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">(See </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Recent Developments in the Roads P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">rogramme for England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, John W. Smith, RAC Foundation, July 2013)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">A review of overseas experience of funding and financing roads is to be found here: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Providing and funding strategic roads: an international perspective with lesions from the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, Smith </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">et al </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ARUP and RAC Foundation, November 2011.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">How should the Highways Agency be reformed to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the strategic road network?</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We agr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ee with the White Paper (para. 16): “Any change needs to be one that motorists can trust, but experience from other sectors and other countries shows that there could be new ways of running the roads which might work for the benefit of all road users.” The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> July 2013 announcements include a commitment to create an independent oversight body, or “watchdog”.  This element of governance of the Strategic Road Network is currently absent, although it is to be found in all other public utilities. To repair this is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> important because the overriding requirement for delivery of the roads reform is that it should win the trust of road users and the public in general. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Arguably, the separation of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> HA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> is not, in itself an important reform. But it could become an import</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ant step towards a much more fundamental change in which ownership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.  If the public has no appetite for a full privatisat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ion the mutual or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">statutory public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">trust offer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">viable alternative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">These alternative models of governance are discussed in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">rning and Paying for England’s Roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">op. cit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">This could accompany a change in the charging regime from the present road tax system to, in full or in part, charging on a pay-as-you-go basis. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Press coverage and survey evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> (see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Ipsos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> MORI motorway charging survey summary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, D. Bayliss, RAC Foundation, Jun 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> suggest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> that, with or without justification, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> are unconvinced about the success of the utility privatisations and they ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">y resist a reform that is mis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">perceived as anot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">her privatisation, or a step in that direction. Further, the price of road fuels is a significant issue and the public are well aware that a large proportion of that price is tax, only a minority share of which is spent on funding roads.  To make matters w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">orse the condition of roads—particularly local authority roads—has been allowed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> deteriorate for lack of funding and the public are particularly sensitive to this deterioration in the quality of the public realm. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">This has created an entrenched cynicism </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">leading to an assumption that any reform is likely to be an attempt to charge the motorist more “by stealth” without necessarily improving their experience as a consumer.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">he public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">must be persuaded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> that if the new body is able to hold this government an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">d future governments to the promises made in 2013 then road conditions will be better than they would have been under continuation of old policies.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">It is therefore essential that the new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">“watchdog”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> be clearly independent of all interests. The utility regul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ators have secured power and influence because in statute and in practice they are independent of Parliament, government and users: they answer only to the courts.  The role of the roads watchdog must be seen to be distinct from that of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">lobby group. Cert</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ainly, it should take full account of the interests of road users and others, but in a balanced and objective manner.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">There are sev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">eral functions to be performed: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">act as an independent and trusted source of information about the efficiency with which the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">new</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> HA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> is performing; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">assess and report the conditions to which the assets are being maintained and provide a view of future expenditure necessary to deliver asset</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> condition to a specified level; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">act as an independent and trusted source of information on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the level of service b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">eing experienced by road users; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">comment on whether the funding the Government is making available is, or is not commensurate with the periodic Roads Investment Strategy that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ministers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> will have  agreed with the new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">HA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">; t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">o adjudicate w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">hether what the new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">HA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> has committed to under each five-year Roads Investment Strategy is actually delivered. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> leads to the question of what p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">owers the new body would have. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">If it is to have a duty to give force to the notion that the Roads Investment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Strategy is legally binding then it would need the commensurate powers. Otherwise, somebody else would need those powers. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The interfaces between the Strategic Road Network and local authority roads have always been a source of friction and may become more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> so as the Highways Agency gains a degree of independence.  There is a question as to whether the watchdog body would have a dispute resolution or “honest broker” role. Maybe the watchdog should have some formal locus in holding local authorities to accoun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">t for the condition of the local network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, at least those parts of it with regional or nati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">onal importance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, at least as far as some of the roads more important from a national or regional perspective.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">HA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> has and will continue to have a large number of c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ontracts for supply with private sector providers. There are a number of shadow tolled PFI schemes.  Presumably these will continue to be regulated under the conventional laws of contract.  There is a question as to whether the new watchdog could usefully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">become involved in regulating the letting or management of agreements with private providers in these cases? A reason for considering this is that if the watchdog is constituted as an independent body with powers then potential private investors may be mor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">e attracted because they perceive the policy risk and the political risk as being mitigated. Protection of the interests of private investors is an important (but often un-noticed) function of the utility regulators.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">It is tempting to suggest that a new bo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">dy would become a new function for existing institution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> such as the Office of Rail Regulation or Passenger Focus, on the grounds that by avoiding setting up a new body expense would be avoided.  This argument needs to be tested.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">t will have to be proper</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ly resourced whether it is free-standing or part of an existing body. This is going to be quite a substantial task and institutions such as the ORR are already fully stretched. There is a danger of sheer complexity compromising the competence of both a “ho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">st” institution and the new watchdog.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">October</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> 201</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">3</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">              </span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:left;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>